What were we talking about?

57:53.260 --> 57:54.662
Oh, the Chicano Moratorium.

57:54.922 --> 57:55.503
Oh, yeah.

57:55.523 --> 57:56.704
Let me get to the Chicano Moratorium.

57:56.724 --> 57:57.465
Okay, okay, okay.

57:59.133 --> 58:23.827
I got a little bit off of that only because what happened in that Southwest tour of 1970, which was before the moratorium, is that as we went out, we took an acto that we had just put together for the Chicano moratorium called Vietnam Campesino, which talked about the U.S.

58:25.089 --> 58:28.093
agricultural and military

58:29.440 --> 58:32.724
complex or whatever you want to call it.

58:32.744 --> 58:33.125
Industrial complex.

58:33.145 --> 58:34.507
Yes.

58:34.527 --> 58:50.747
And that at one point during the Vietnam War, the army, the military was buying all the scab, lettuce, and grapes from the growers to undo the grape strike and all of that.

58:50.767 --> 58:50.868
Yeah.

58:50.888 --> 58:52.189
So they were in cahoots.

58:53.010 --> 58:58.958
So when we saw that, part of our... So we decided to do this act of Vietnam Campesino.

58:59.360 --> 59:02.584
to show how the U.S.

59:02.644 --> 59:18.642
military agriculture complex was helping out growers by taking and buying all this shit and how they were affecting the farm workers in California, but then how they were napalming and affecting the campesino, the poor Vietnamese campesino.

59:19.302 --> 59:24.909
And they were using Chicanos as soldiers to go do it.

59:25.449 --> 59:28.793
And that's kind of like the whole focus of that acto.

59:29.347 --> 59:43.148
And so when we went on this tour, we were the propaganda arm, our own self propaganda arm.

59:43.168 --> 59:47.274
Nobody said, oh, can Teatro be the propaganda arm of the Chicano Moratorium?

59:47.435 --> 59:47.615
No.

59:48.156 --> 59:49.698
We just knew what to do.

59:50.700 --> 59:58.071
So we went on this tour, and every town that we went to, we're telling them, August 29th, we're going to have a

59:58.675 --> 01:00:01.479
Massive marcha in Los Angeles.

01:00:01.840 --> 01:00:04.564
You need to come.

01:00:04.584 --> 01:00:08.970
So Denver, New Mexico, Arizona, Texas.

01:00:10.453 --> 01:00:13.277
And I think that's why we got so many people from everywhere.

01:00:13.958 --> 01:00:15.240
Because we were the only ones doing it.

01:00:15.260 --> 01:00:16.161
We didn't have internet.

01:00:16.181 --> 01:00:18.344
We didn't have people on phones calling.

01:00:18.364 --> 01:00:20.948
We didn't have Facebook or Twitter.

01:00:21.669 --> 01:00:24.133
So we did that.

01:00:26.056 --> 01:00:26.877
And...

01:00:27.903 --> 01:00:30.908
And thousands showed up.

01:00:30.928 --> 01:00:52.100
And we were there in the middle of this because not only were we protesting the killing of Chicanos in the Vietnam War and protesting against it, but people were also advocating for education, for all these different other issues.

01:00:52.761 --> 01:00:54.143
And that's what that marcha became.

01:00:54.183 --> 01:00:56.627
It became a rallying point

01:00:57.012 --> 01:01:00.095
for all these things.

01:01:00.115 --> 01:01:08.483
And we were in Fresno, getting ready to drive down there, and everybody was going in different cars.

01:01:09.404 --> 01:01:15.189
And I remember I went with Phil in his car, and I took my brother Carlos with me.

01:01:15.770 --> 01:01:16.991
He was only like 16.

01:01:18.793 --> 01:01:24.218
And we got in the car, and then just before we took off from Fresno, one of the

01:01:26.915 --> 01:01:36.829
Phil says, oh, I've got to stop over at the Brown Beret office because they want to know if we can carry some stuff in our trunk.

01:01:38.191 --> 01:01:39.612
Okay, so we drive over there.

01:01:40.073 --> 01:01:43.298
And Phil is, are you talking about Phil Esparza?

01:01:43.358 --> 01:01:43.598
Yeah.

01:01:44.679 --> 01:01:52.310
He and I became friends when I first went to Fresno and that's how I ended up becoming a part of the theater because he took me to the place.

01:01:52.811 --> 01:01:56.736
So anyway, open up the trunk and here come the Brown Beret's

01:01:57.239 --> 01:02:03.529
with duffel bags full of rifles and guns.

01:02:03.549 --> 01:02:04.791
I mean, weapons.

01:02:04.811 --> 01:02:05.893
I said, holy shit.

01:02:06.574 --> 01:02:10.260
So we put them in there and Phil's like .

01:02:10.280 --> 01:02:11.543
You didn't know what they were breaking.

01:02:12.304 --> 01:02:15.329
We closed the thing and now we're headed to LA.

01:02:16.290 --> 01:02:23.382
And so it turns out that they were going there to

01:02:24.205 --> 01:02:29.512
be the protectors, the defenders or whatever, but they were taking real good.

01:02:29.532 --> 01:02:45.152
And so anyway, before we get there, I'm already, you know, thinking ahead and going, oh, shit, this is going to be, this is going to be a slaughter of Raza, not them.

01:02:46.113 --> 01:02:50.219
And I, and I, so I had a pre, what, a premonition?

01:02:50.359 --> 01:02:51.140
Premonition.

01:02:51.941 --> 01:02:53.503
So anyway, we get there and

01:02:53.905 --> 01:02:59.893
The park is getting full of people, and Brown Berets are all around the perimeter, you know, doing their thing.

01:03:00.995 --> 01:03:08.024
And so I don't know where the guns ended up, but I was over there by the stage area with my brother, and we're getting ready to go on.

01:03:08.946 --> 01:03:15.515
We're going to do a couple of songs and some actos when shit starts breaking out at the corner.

01:03:15.815 --> 01:03:22.444
We're here on the stage, and that corner, we start seeing, ah, look like a goddamn...

01:03:22.863 --> 01:03:26.068
you know, those battles where people are just .

01:03:26.088 --> 01:03:36.084
And it was starting there, and they were shooting canisters of gas into the crowd, toward the stage, everywhere, just .

01:03:36.104 --> 01:03:37.005
It was all out battle.

01:03:38.187 --> 01:03:43.355
And I turn around like this, looking for Carlos, and he's not there.

01:03:44.016 --> 01:03:45.258
He's gone.

01:03:45.278 --> 01:03:48.804
So I'm looking for him, and everybody's running away.

01:03:49.605 --> 01:03:49.765
Yeah.

01:03:50.268 --> 01:03:53.833
And I'm looking for my brother, and I can't find him, so I go into the middle of the thing.

01:03:54.815 --> 01:03:59.081
And way over there at the front, what's happening, automatic organization.

01:03:59.782 --> 01:04:15.465
People, men, are all hooking up arms and making a barrier, a wall, to keep the police from getting through and getting to the kids and the women and everybody else that was there, old ladies, grandma, didn't give a shit.

01:04:16.205 --> 01:04:25.255
So there's one, two, three, there's like three or four lines like this, all vatos just getting like that.

01:04:25.275 --> 01:04:26.677
Because they don't have weapons.

01:04:26.697 --> 01:04:30.962
So I look over there and I see Carlos.

01:04:30.982 --> 01:04:32.163
He's in the first.

01:04:33.024 --> 01:04:38.009
And he's standing there like that.

01:04:39.171 --> 01:04:42.955
And I see one of them goes over there and boom, whacks him.

01:04:43.441 --> 01:04:46.565
And so, man, I just made a beeline for him.

01:04:46.605 --> 01:04:48.047
I didn't give a shit about anything.

01:04:48.127 --> 01:04:50.870
Just... And got him.

01:04:51.531 --> 01:04:54.034
And we're... I was trying to get him out of there.

01:04:54.395 --> 01:04:55.236
Let's get out of here.

01:04:55.336 --> 01:04:55.776
Let's go.

01:04:55.917 --> 01:04:56.017
Boom.

01:04:56.037 --> 01:04:57.078
I didn't even know where to go.

01:04:57.479 --> 01:04:58.039
I didn't know L.A.

01:04:59.461 --> 01:05:04.027
So... I remember I got tripped up or knocked down.

01:05:04.067 --> 01:05:04.908
And I'm on the floor.

01:05:05.068 --> 01:05:09.133
And this cop with a riot helmet and everything comes over.

01:05:09.173 --> 01:05:10.235
And he's about to hit me.

01:05:11.897 --> 01:05:12.958
And this other Chicano...

01:05:14.255 --> 01:05:20.763
out of nowhere with one of those jumbo quarts of beer.

01:05:21.204 --> 01:05:22.966
Yeah.

01:05:22.986 --> 01:05:23.827
And the cops.

01:05:23.847 --> 01:05:24.929
Yeah, knocks them out.

01:05:25.990 --> 01:05:31.297
And so I get up and grab my brother and head out to the exterior perimeter.

01:05:32.018 --> 01:05:35.202
And then we're just, we got maced the whole thing.

01:05:35.242 --> 01:05:43.553
There's this little old lady in her yard throwing water on people and she's, so we went through all of that and we're ducking

01:05:44.107 --> 01:05:45.088
Rocks, brakes.

01:05:45.168 --> 01:05:46.950
I mean, it's total mayhem.

01:05:48.632 --> 01:05:50.454
Cars are getting overturned, burned.

01:05:50.954 --> 01:05:52.256
Police cars, everything.

01:05:52.316 --> 01:05:53.677
Police are zipping through there.

01:05:54.658 --> 01:06:03.388
And then we end up, finally, after three or four hours of this, we end up all exhausted, sitting in a corner street.

01:06:05.550 --> 01:06:11.597
And this Volkswagen bug, not bug, van, drives up to us, and there's two girls in there.

01:06:12.798 --> 01:06:13.759
Where are you guys from?

01:06:14.110 --> 01:06:18.356
So we're from Fresno, and we've lost our people.

01:06:18.957 --> 01:06:20.820
Jump in, we'll take you to a safe house.

01:06:21.521 --> 01:06:22.102
So we jump in.

01:06:22.723 --> 01:06:23.905
Yeah, they were rescuing people.

01:06:24.686 --> 01:06:38.386
So we ended up at their house, and it was UCLA Ballet Folklórico girls in their house.

01:06:38.406 --> 01:06:42.092
So we ended up staying there that night, and...

01:06:42.207 --> 01:06:50.137
That night, as we were waiting, we were trying to find out if we could find somebody that was going back to Fresno, hitch a ride back.

01:06:50.157 --> 01:06:59.850
But that night, we were at their house, and the girls said, oh, we're all going over to the something, some club.

01:07:01.031 --> 01:07:05.637
And I said, and they were saying, yeah, come with us, blah, blah, blah.

01:07:05.657 --> 01:07:08.601
We go there, and who's performing at this rinky-dink club?

01:07:08.842 --> 01:07:11.385
El Chicano.

01:07:11.405 --> 01:07:11.505
What?

01:07:12.616 --> 01:07:13.637
That's what it was.

01:07:13.658 --> 01:07:15.580
They were just performing in some bar.

01:07:15.921 --> 01:07:17.163
Who is El Chicano?

01:07:17.183 --> 01:07:18.905
You don't know who El Chicano is?

01:07:19.125 --> 01:07:19.566
No.

01:07:20.367 --> 01:07:21.469
It's a Chicano rock band.

01:07:22.230 --> 01:07:23.291
I'll play you some of their music.

01:07:24.914 --> 01:07:29.020
So anyway, the next morning, and we stayed there with them that night.

01:07:29.040 --> 01:07:33.066
And then the next day, we got a ride.

01:07:34.488 --> 01:07:37.232
Somebody that was going back to Fresno.

01:07:37.732 --> 01:07:39.535
And it turned out to be Richard.

01:07:41.405 --> 01:07:43.409
Shit, I can't think of the guy's last name right now.

01:07:44.130 --> 01:07:45.652
Richard Duran.

01:07:45.672 --> 01:07:46.895
Ricardo Duran.

01:07:47.135 --> 01:07:47.896
No number Richard.

01:07:47.916 --> 01:07:50.421
It's not Ricardo Duran.

01:07:50.441 --> 01:07:54.909
And so we hitch a ride with him, and he takes us back to Fresno, and then we get back home.

01:07:55.450 --> 01:07:58.154
Everybody from the theater is already back in Fresno.

01:07:58.174 --> 01:07:59.717
We were wondering what happened to you.

01:08:04.118 --> 01:08:29.535
abandoned and um so anyway so so the chicano moratorium then became the chicano moratorium because of all of that shit that happened yeah but the background was that i was a part of an organized effort that the only organized effort that went out and promoted it to communities outside of california through the theater um

01:08:32.975 --> 01:08:43.753
That is also the tour, 1970, where we were performing in Tierra Maria in this little, I don't know if it was a church or a little school.

01:08:45.376 --> 01:08:52.628
And at the end of the performance, we ended up, because this is how we traveled, we said, anybody have room for us to stay?

01:08:52.728 --> 01:08:54.771
We can sleep on the floor or whatever, you know?

01:08:55.492 --> 01:08:58.257
And so this guy gets up and goes, I can take six of you.

01:08:59.198 --> 01:09:01.001
Was it Dennis Hopper?

01:09:01.021 --> 01:09:01.662
Yep.

01:09:01.682 --> 01:09:02.423
Dennis Hopper.

01:09:03.224 --> 01:09:07.490
So we ended up staying with Dennis Hopper like for three or four days at his hacienda.

01:09:09.634 --> 01:09:10.775
With his personal cook.

01:09:10.795 --> 01:09:19.148
I always had all these opposite contrasts through all this stuff.

01:09:19.168 --> 01:09:19.268
Yeah.

01:09:19.288 --> 01:09:28.682
But what I learned from the people there in Tierra Maria in New Mexico with the Dennis Hoppers and all that is that the local Mexicano community

01:09:29.253 --> 01:09:46.401
was feeling oppressed, exploited, and their stuff being appropriated because they were being invaded by white hippies.

01:09:46.567 --> 01:09:49.150
Like Dennis Hopper?

01:09:49.731 --> 01:09:49.971
Yeah.

01:09:49.991 --> 01:09:53.235
By setting up their little communes and all of that.

01:09:53.495 --> 01:09:53.835
Yeah.

01:09:54.516 --> 01:09:58.040
And just affecting their way of being, their way of life.

01:09:58.801 --> 01:09:59.502
So I remember that.

01:09:59.662 --> 01:10:02.265
That also added to my sense of Chigarismo.

01:10:04.187 --> 01:10:09.253
Can I ask you about, you know the term Reconquista, right?

01:10:09.273 --> 01:10:09.373
Yeah.

01:10:10.014 --> 01:10:13.097
Would you say, because I know you had mentioned that

01:10:13.567 --> 01:10:25.566
For you, you felt like part of what you understood as Chicanismo was a reclamation of territory, culture, spirituality, ways of life, ways of knowing.

01:10:25.586 --> 01:10:29.712
Would you lump that in with that idea of Reconquista?

01:10:29.732 --> 01:10:36.824
Yeah, that's Chicanos at their most nationalist perspective.

01:10:37.324 --> 01:10:37.785
In other words,

01:10:38.508 --> 01:10:43.295
They don't go beyond the, hey, this is our land, fuck you, get out.

01:10:43.315 --> 01:10:43.556
Yeah.

01:10:43.576 --> 01:10:45.399
I mean, there's that group out there, too.

01:10:46.200 --> 01:10:46.360
Yeah.

01:10:46.380 --> 01:10:46.480
Okay?

01:10:47.902 --> 01:10:55.835
And so they organized the Marcha de la Reconquista from the border all the way to Sacramento.

01:10:55.855 --> 01:10:56.956
And they went through Livingston.

01:10:57.016 --> 01:10:59.660
As a matter of fact, they stayed in Livingston overnight.

01:11:01.583 --> 01:11:02.224
When was that?

01:11:03.166 --> 01:11:05.089
1970-something.

01:11:05.169 --> 01:11:06.591
I don't remember the year.

01:11:06.925 --> 01:11:08.427
I mean, you could probably look it up.

01:11:08.527 --> 01:11:14.072
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:11:14.092 --> 01:11:20.379
So your grandmother actually got involved in some of that because she helped coordinate their stay there and all that in Livingston.

01:11:20.899 --> 01:11:28.427
But she was also a part of the Degana Huida Quetzalcoatl University and the takeover of that naval station.

01:11:29.248 --> 01:11:30.529
Over by Davis?

01:11:31.090 --> 01:11:31.330
Yep.

01:11:31.350 --> 01:11:32.511
And she was a part of the...

01:11:33.284 --> 01:11:35.107
occupiers.

01:11:35.127 --> 01:11:42.237
And she was viewed as the Chicana spokesperson for that, for that group.

01:11:43.499 --> 01:11:46.363
The native spokesperson was somebody else.

01:11:46.383 --> 01:11:47.986
Yeah.

01:11:48.006 --> 01:11:48.106
Okay.

01:11:48.226 --> 01:11:54.095
And then let me ask you about the idea of Aslan, right?

01:11:55.417 --> 01:11:58.161
Because you had mentioned earlier that

01:11:58.647 --> 01:12:05.074
you know, oh, I had understood or, like, I learned about this story, right?

01:12:05.674 --> 01:12:10.399
Whether from, like, other communities that you had interacted with.

01:12:11.761 --> 01:12:22.592
And so I was kind of wondering, or actually what you said was that you had found out that they had similar kind of stories, right?

01:12:22.672 --> 01:12:28.138
Or stories that, like, kind of corroborated things that you had already heard about.

01:12:28.338 --> 01:12:28.418
BBs.

01:12:28.870 --> 01:12:33.077
Histories, stories, cultural practices.

01:12:33.318 --> 01:12:40.170
Yeah, so what I wanted to know was where did you first learn about that?

01:12:41.472 --> 01:12:43.256
Of that idea?

01:12:43.636 --> 01:12:49.727
Yeah, that idea of Aslan or that there were people from a certain area that migrated.

01:12:50.368 --> 01:12:52.452
I learned about it.

01:12:53.313 --> 01:12:54.836
I think that's Chewy.

01:12:54.856 --> 01:12:55.758
Hold on.

